<span class="header1">WRITTEN & ORAL COMMUNICATIONS</span>
<p>These occupations need people who can write well and enjoy public 
speaking. If speaking in front of large groups does not bother you, 
the occupations in this field may be appropriate.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Scientific or Technical Publications 
Editor</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BE/43289.jpg" 
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Scientific or Technical 
Publications Editor" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>To be a scientific or technical publications 
editor, you must be a good writer.  You must also be interested in 
science or technology.  As an editor, you would read scientific or 
technical materials as they are being written.  You would make 
suggestions for changes that would make them easier to understand.  
Editors often use computers to make their editing 
changes.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need at least a Bachelor's Degree in 
communications, journalism, or English for this job.  Many editors 
have been promoted from the writing staff.  Also, your work 
experience will be very important to finding a job.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>An editor can make anywhere from $24,000 to 
$76,000.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Editorial Assistant</span><br /><br />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>As an editorial assistant you would work closely 
with an editor.  You would check to be sure that the grammar, 
spelling, and sentence structure were correct. You would also be 
sure that any facts, dates and other information were 
correct.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need at least a Bachelor's Degree in 
communications, journalism, or English for this job.  Volunteer work 
on yearbooks and school newspapers can give you 
experience.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>An editorial assistant may earn form $16,000 to 
$60,000.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Reporter</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BE/43293.jpg" 
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Reporter" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>If you like to look for clues and piece stories 
together, you might become a reporter. As a reporter, you would 
research "a lead" or information about a possible newsworthy story. 
You would then write the story using the facts you found through 
your research.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need at least a Bachelor's Degree in 
communications, journalism, or English for this job.  Experience at 
a newspaper or broadcast studio is helpful too.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary ranges from $18,000 to 
$69,000+.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

<span class="header1">COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGIES</span>
<p>The occupations in this field are very important to our everyday 
routines. They allow you to come in contact with large numbers of 
people.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header3">Traffic Engineer</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BE/1099.jpg" 
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Traffic Engineer" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A traffic engineer decides where the traffic 
lights go and how long the lights stay red or green.  As a traffic 
engineer, you would design traffic lights, road signs, and pavement 
markings. You would use your computer to make sure that traffic 
lights are set to allow traffic to flow smoothly.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>A traffic engineer must have at least a 
Bachelor's Degree and be registered in the state where he/she 
works.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly income ranges from $25,000 to 
$85,000+.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Radio Operator</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BE/M100.jpg" 
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Radio Operator" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A radio operator often works for the military. 
In this job, you would send, receive, and log radio messages. 
Sometimes you would figure out secret codes.  This is an important 
job. Without radio operators, it would be hard to communicate within 
the military.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You do not need a college degree for this job.  
But courses in typing, speech, and English will be valuable. The 
military will train you in radio operation.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The yearly salary you receive in any branch of 
the military is based on your rank, the number of years of service, 
and the job you have.</blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Broadcast Technician</span><br /><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/BE/1102.jpg" 
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Broadcast Technician" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>A broadcast technician helps set up, repair, and 
operate the equipment used to send radio and television signals. 
Technicians operate the cameras.  They also create lighting effects 
and develop sound tracks. You might enjoy this job if you like 
working with equipment and do not mind getting your hands 
dirty.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>You need some post high school courses for this 
job.  Many technicians attend 2 or 3-year programs at vocational 
technical institutions.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>A technician can start a job at $20,000. You 
salary will depend on the amount of education and experience you 
have.</blockquote>

